==Managerial career==
===Ham-Kam===
In 2002, Solbakken returned to Norway and started his managerial career at his old club HamKam, positioned at the second tier. He had great success at HamKam, as the club won the league and was promoted to the top-flight Tippeligaen. His "resurrection", and the "salvation" (i.e. promotion) of HamKam, earned him the nickname "Ståle Salvatore", often cited in Norwegian press since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vg.no/sport/fotball/ligaer/tyskland/artikkel.php?artid=10057368|title = Bestekompis Skogheim forbannet etter sparkingen av Solbakken: - Köln legger ikke trenerkabal, de er trenerkannibaler| date=13 April 2012 }}</ref>

The next season, Solbakken managed HamKam to a fifth place in the [[Tippeligaen 2004]] season, and he won the [[Kniksen award#2004|2004 Kniksen award]] as Norwegian Manager of the Year. In late 2005, Solbakken was named as new manager of another of his former clubs, [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]].

===Copenhagen===
In his first years at the club, Solbakken guided Copenhagen to the [[2005–06 Danish Superliga|2006]] and [[2006–07 Danish Superliga|2007]] [[Danish Superliga]] championship, as well as the [[Royal League 2005–06|2006]] [[Royal League]] trophy. He managed Copenhagen through to the group stage of the [[2006–07 UEFA Champions League]], after beating [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in the final qualifying round on 23 August 2006. Copenhagen finished last in its group, though they won a meriting 1–0 victory against later semi-finalists [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].

In May 2009, Solbakken led Copenhagen to [[Double (association football)|the Double]] of both the [[2008–09 Danish Cup|2009 Danish Cup]] and the [[2008–09 Danish Superliga|2009 Superliga]] championship, the seventh championship in club history. On 3 November 2009, it was announced that he would not renew his contract which ended on 30 June 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fck.dk/index.php?pageid=754&newsid=9768 |title=Ståle Solbakken bliver norsk landstræner i 2012 |date=3 November 2009 |access-date=3 November 2009 |language=da |publisher=[[F.C. Copenhagen]]}}</ref> Instead, he agreed a [[letter of intent]] to become Norway national team manager either in January 2012 or after the [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]], should Norway qualify.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fotball.no/Landslag_og_toppfotball/Landslag/A-menn/2009/Olsen-fortsetter-og-etterfolges-av-Solbakken/ |title=Olsen fortsetter og etterfølges av Solbakken |date=3 November 2009 |access-date=3 November 2009 |language=no |publisher=[[Football Association of Norway]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120524125015/http://www.fotball.no/Landslag_og_toppfotball/Landslag/A-menn/2009/Olsen-fortsetter-og-etterfolges-av-Solbakken/ |archive-date=24 May 2012 }}</ref> However, this agreement was ultimately not to come to fruition.

===1. FC Köln===
On 15 May 2011, it was announced that Solbakken would take over as manager of [[1. FC Köln]]<ref name="Solbakken neuer FC-Coach - Kreuzbandriss bei Petit">{{cite news|title=Solbakken neuer FC-Coach - Kreuzbandriss bei Petit|url=https://www.kicker.de/solbakken-neuer-fc-coach---kreuzbandriss-bei-petit-552488/artikel|access-date=21 August 2014|publisher=kicker|date=15 May 2011|language=de}}</ref> of the German [[Bundesliga]] from [[Director of football|sporting director]] [[Volker Finke]], who acted as interim manager after [[Frank Schaefer (football manager)|Frank Schaefer]] quit during the season.<ref name="Köln">{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/1956/europe/2011/05/14/2486732/koln-confirm-stale-solbakken-as-new-coach-for-next-season/ |title=Köln confirm Stale Solbakken as new manager for next season |date=14 May 2011 |publisher=goal.com}}</ref> Solbakken had been due to take the Norway national team job in January 2012, but Köln bought out his contract for a reported €400,000.<ref name="Köln" />

He won his first game in charge, a [[DFB-Pokal|DFB Cup]] tie at [[SC Wiedenbrück 2000|SC Wiedenbrück]], but took four league games to register his first victory. By the winter break Köln sat in tenth place, but their form plummeted in the second half of the campaign and they dropped into a relegation battle. This decline in form was coupled with several negative incidents involving their squad misbehaving off the field.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/solbakken-arrives-at-wolves--well-schooled-in-dealing-with-turmoil-7737892.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220525/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/solbakken-arrives-at-wolves--well-schooled-in-dealing-with-turmoil-7737892.html |archive-date=25 May 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Solbakken arrives at Wolves – well schooled in dealing with turmoil |date=12 May 2012 |work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> Solbakken later quipped that "[[Jesus]] and [[José Mourinho]] would have struggled together at that club this year".<ref>{{cite news |title=Ståle Solbakken defends failure at Cologne after taking reins at Wolves |url=https://www.thetimes.com/article/stale-solbakken-defends-failure-at-cologne-after-taking-reins-at-wolves-527skd0xrgm |access-date=27 August 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=14 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Morgan defends Solbakken appointment |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/soccer/arid-30551443.html |access-date=27 August 2020 |work=Irish Examiner |date=14 May 2012}}</ref>

Solbakken was dismissed by Köln on 12 April 2012<ref name="Köln entlässt Solbakken - Schaefer hilft aus">{{cite news|title=Köln entlässt Solbakken - Schaefer hilft aus|url=https://www.kicker.de/koeln-entlaesst-solbakken---schaefer-hilft-aus-567421/artikel|access-date=21 August 2014|publisher=kicker|date=12 April 2012|language=de}}</ref> following a 0–4 loss at [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz]], with the team sat in 16th place. He was replaced by former coach [[Frank Schaefer (football manager)|Frank Schaefer]], who oversaw the final four games of the season, during which the club dropped to 17th place and were therefore relegated.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/61143/1-fc-köln-vs-fc-bayern-münchen/report |title=1. FC Köln vs FC Bayern München Report |date=5 May 2012 |publisher=goal.com}}</ref>

===Wolverhampton Wanderers===
On 11 May 2012, English club [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] announced that Solbakken was to become their new manager. He officially took over from acting manager [[Terry Connor]] on 1 July 2012.<ref name="Wolves appoint Norwegian Stale Solbakken as new manager">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/18030227 |title=Wolves appoint Norwegian Stale Solbakken as new manager |date=11 May 2012 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> Solbakken began his Wolves tenure with the club in the [[Football League Championship]] having been relegated from the [[Premier League|English Premier League]] at the end of the 2011–12 season. His first competitive game in charge was a [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]], which his side won on penalties.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/19124054 |title=Wolves 1-1 Aldershot |date=11 August 2012 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref>

Solbakken failed to stop the club's slump that had brought relegation and despite at one time lifting the club to third place, they had slumped as low as 18th by the turn of the year. He was sacked on 5 January 2013, following an [[FA Cup]] elimination by at that time non-league [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]], which was his fourth consecutive defeat.<ref name="Wolves sack manager Stale Solbakken after six months">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20870241 |title=Wolves sack manager Stale Solbakken after six months |date=5 January 2013 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref>

===Return to Copenhagen===
On 21 August 2013, Solbakken returned as head coach of [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]], two years after his departure.<ref name="FCK fyrer Jacobs - ansætter Ståle Solbakken">{{cite web |url=http://ekstrabladet.dk/sport/fodbold/dansk_fodbold/superligaen/fc_koebenhavn/article2073373.ece|title=FCK fyrer Jacobs - ansætter Ståle Solbakken|date=21 August 2013 |publisher=Ekstrabladetek|language=da}}</ref>

Solbakken had a seven-year reign at Copenhagen in which he won three championships in 2016, 2017 and 2019. However, due to a bad start to the [[2020–21 Danish Superliga]], poor domestic results during 2020 and a failure to qualify for the [[2020–21 UEFA Europa League]] group stage, Solbakken was fired as manager on 10 October 2020.<ref name="Kæmpe bombe: FCK fyrer Ståle Solbakken">{{cite web|title=Kæmpe bombe: FCK fyrer Ståle Solbakken|language=da|date=10 October 2020|access-date=10 October 2020|publisher=bold.dk|url=https://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/kaempe-bombe-fck-fyrer-staale-solbakken/}}</ref>

For his two tenures at Copenhagen, Solbakken was awarded the title as the 'Biggest Manager in Superliga History' by a jury of 38 experts on the Danish Superliga including former Danish national coach [[Morten Olsen]] and former football player [[Rasmus Würtz]], who is accredited with most Superliga games played to date with 452 caps.<ref name="Superligaens største træner er kåret: Ståle Solbakken løber med hæderen">{{cite web|title=Superligaens største træner er kåret: Ståle Solbakken løber med hæderen|language=da|date=8 March 2022|access-date=8 March 2022|publisher=campo.dk|url=https://www.campo.dk/2022/03/06/superligaens-stoerste-traener-er-kaaret-staale-solbakken-loeber-med-haederen/}}</ref>

===Norway national team===
On 3 December 2020, Solbakken became the Norway international manager on a four-year deal, after the resignation of [[Lars Lagerbäck]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=Joe |title=Former Wolves chief Stale Solbakken lands Norway job |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2020/12/03/former-wolves-chief-stale-solbakken-lands-norway-job/ |access-date=26 January 2021 |work=Express & Star |date=3 December 2020}}</ref> In his first match the following 24 March, the side won 3–0 away to [[Gibraltar national football team|Gibraltar]] in [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] qualification.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Berg Ould-Saada |first1=Arilas |last2=Tinius Folvik |first2=Herman |last3=Baardsen |first3=Joachim |last4=Vesteng |first4=Camilla |title=Ødegaard svarer om skaden etter seier i Solbakkens debut: – litt sårt|url=https://www.vg.no/sport/fotball/i/Epvn53/oedegaard-svarer-om-skaden-etter-seier-i-solbakkens-debut-litt-saart |access-date=14 August 2021 |work=VG |date=25 March 2021 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> Norway failed to qualify, and Solbakken criticised the decision to host the tournament in Qatar due to human rights issues and the manner of the vote; the [[Norwegian Football Federation]] sent only one representative, an analyst to monitor the team's next opponents, [[Spain national football team|Spain]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Manning |first1=Gordon |title=Norway manager critical of World Cup in Qatar and won't be attending event |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/2022/11/17/norway-manager-critical-of-world-cup-in-qatar-and-wont-be-attending-event/ |access-date=22 December 2022 |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=17 November 2022}}</ref>

In the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]] campaign, Solbakken led Norway to qualification for the tournament,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Norway make long-awaited World Cup return |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/norway-qualify-2026}}</ref> finishing top of their group ahead of Italy and securing qualification with a 4–1 victory over Italy in their final match.

==Personal life==
His son [[Markus Solbakken]] is a footballer, who made his debut for the Norwegian national team under his father’s management in 2023.

